Here's my somewhat long example:

https://psalm.dev/r/33c0431227
```
<?php


/**
 * @template I as array-key
 * @template K as array-key
 * @template V
 */
class Converter
{
    /**
     * @var Generator<I,array<K,V>,mixed,void>
     */
    protected $records;

    /**
     * @param Generator<I,array<K,V>,mixed,void> $records
     */
    public function __construct(Generator $records)
    {
        $this->records = $records;
    }
}

/**
 * @template I as array-key
 * @template T
 */
class Collector
{
    /**
     * @var Generator<I,T,mixed,void>
     */
    protected $records;
    
    /**
     * @param Generator<I,T,mixed,void> $records
     */
    public function __construct(Generator $records)
    {
        $this->records = $records;
    }
}

/**
 * @template I as array-key
 * @template K as array-key
 * @template V
 *
 * @extends Collector<I,array<K, V>>
 */
class Selector extends Collector
{
    /**
     * @param Generator<I,array<K,V>,mixed,void> $records
     */
    public function __construct(Generator $records)
    {
        parent::__construct($records);
    }
    
    /**
     * @return Converter<I,K,V>
     */
    public function f()
    {
        return new Converter($this->records);
    }
}

/**
 * @template I as array-key
 * @template K as array-key
 * @template V
 */
class Selector2
{
    /**
     * @var Generator<I,array<K,V>,mixed,void>
     */
    private $records;
    
    /**
     * @param Generator<I,array<K,V>,mixed,void> $records
     */
    public function __construct(Generator $records)
    {
        $this->records = $records;
    }
    
    /**
     * @return Converter<I,K,V>
     */
    public function f()
    {
        return new Converter($this->records);
    }
}
```

`I` is the index type, and `T` is the element type, which sometimes can be `T = array<K, V>`.

There's a difference between how psalm (dev-master 7543253) sees the `I`. In `Selector` it resolves it down to `array-key`, but in `Selector2` it's `I as array-key`.

Here's the exact message:

> ERROR: InvalidReturnStatement - 67:16 - The inferred type 'Converter<array-key, K:Selector as array-key, V:Selector as mixed>' does not match the declared return type 'Converter<I:Selector as array-key, K:Selector as array-key, V:Selector as mixed>' for Selector::f
